The paper deals with clustering, which is a common topic in machine learning and data science. The method presented in the paper is general and can be applied to different types of data, including Euclidean data, kernelized data, and data derived from information spaces. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CL (Computation and Language), and cs.CV (Computer Vision). However, given the focus on clustering and the use of affinity scores to validate data memberships, cs.LG and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. The other sub-categories are also relevant, as they deal with related topics such as natural language processing (cs.CL) and image analysis (cs.CV).
